                        <a href="/magazine/toc/2020/07/" title="July/August 2020"
                        data-omni-click="r'',r' ',d,r'magazine-archive',r'0',r''">
                        
                            <figure>
                            <img data-src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/NtZxdWMqWyhY4FR7a4nMS_kuaGQ=/0x0:1995x2666/210x280/filters:format(png)/media/img/issues/2020/06/10/0720_Cover_Redo-1/original.png" class="cover lazyload"
                                alt="July/August 2020"
                                width="105" />
                            </figure>
                        
                            <h2 class="hed">July/Aug 2020</h2>
                        </a>
                        
                            <p class="dek"> Trumps collaborators, the genius of supermarkets, the looming bank collapse, and unloved children. Plus new fiction by Andrew Martin, the end of minimalism, Big Tech and the plague, Kevin Kwan, Ai Weiwei on the pandemic, Lauren Groff on Florida, and more. </p>
                        
                    </li>
                
                
                    <li class=" article" id="back-issue-2" >
                        <a href="/magazine/toc/2020/06/" title="June 2020"
                        data-omni-click="r'',r' ',d,r'magazine-archive',r'1',r''">
                        
                            <figure>
                            <img data-src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/RIW4sQ4xqC2zZW_YHaMJ1huLz2A=/0x0:1995x2666/210x280/filters:format(png)/media/img/issues/2020/06/10/0620_Cover-1/original.png" class="cover lazyload"
                                alt="June 2020"
                                width="105" />
                            </figure>
                        
                            <h2 class="hed">June 2020</h2>
                        </a>
                        
                            <p class="dek"> QAnon and conspiracies, the phantom papyrus, Russian election hacking, and the summer of Snowden. Plus sadcoms, the U.S. as failed state, and birds, with essays by Caitlin Flanagan, Thomas Lynch, Vann R. Newkirk II, and more. </p>
                        
                    </li>
                
                
                    <li class=" article" id="back-issue-3" >
